sbol:Component.sbh:mutableDescription: Bidirectional transcriptional terminator consisting of a 22 bp stem-loop.
sbol:Component.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from luxICDABEG operon terminator of Vibrio fischeri <genbank>AF170104</genbank>.
sbol:Component.sbol:name: BBa_B0011
sbol:Component.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:Component.sbh:mutableNotes: In the naturally-occuring sequence there is a mismatch in the stem of the stem loop. This can be corrected via an A->G mutation (at position 40 -- sequence coordinate/not MFOLD coordinate). The above sequence does not reflect this mutation (but the MFOLD image does). This terminator's location cannot be found using some inverted repeat detectors like PALINDROME because it is too short and contains a mismatch. This one was found with the help of Tom Knight. It lies between two coding regions that point towards eachother.

sbol:Component.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:Component.sbol:name: BBa_B0012
sbol:Component.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:Component.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:Component.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow
sbol:Component.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
